message.content:
The only production rules for the start symbol are  

S → NT2 NT26  
S → NT18 NT11  

So every generated sentence must begin with the first terminal produced by either NT2 or NT18.

1. Which non-terminals can produce the terminal t2?  
   A scan of all single-terminal productions shows that only NT20 → 't2' can do so.

2. Can NT2 start with NT20?  
   NT2’s alternatives are  
   • NT2 → 't42' (begins with t42)  
   • NT2 → NT0 NT20 (begins with whatever NT0 produces)  
   NT0, however, can produce only  
   • 't26'  
   • NT27 NT25  
   • NT0 NT26  
   None of these ultimately yield t2 as their first symbol.  
   Hence any string derived from NT2 begins with t42 or t26, never with t2.

3. Can NT18 start with NT20?  
   NT18’s alternatives are  
   • 't54'  
   • 't23'  
   • NT34 NT30  
   The two single-terminal choices give t54 or t23, not t2.  
   In NT34 NT30, the first token comes from NT34.  
   NT34 can begin with  
   • 't57'  
   • NT2 …  
   • NT10 …  
   As shown above NT2 cannot start with t2, and NT10 starts with t27 or t55, never t2.  
   Therefore NT18 cannot begin with t2 either.

Since neither NT2 nor NT18 can produce a sentence whose very first token is t2, the grammar cannot generate any string that starts with t2. The supplied string does start with t2, so it is not in the language of the grammar.

No

A quick bottom-up analysis of the grammar shows that many of the single-token categories that appear in the sentence (for instance the unique token “t45”, which can only be produced by NT8 → 't45', and the unique token “t41”, which can only come from NT27 → 't41') force any successful parse to pass through very specific non-terminals (NT8 and NT27 respectively).  

Tracing all binary combinations that could incorporate those obligatory symbols rapidly blocks:  

• The only rule that can attach NT8 in a binary way is NT1 → NT13 NT8.  
  – This would require NT13 to cover the immediately adjacent token.  
  – Applying that constraint to the actual token sequence leaves no compatible higher-level rule that can connect the resulting NT1 constituent to its neighbors while still honouring the positions of the other forced categories (NT27 for “t41”, NT31 for every “t24”, etc.).  

• Similarly, any constituent covering the single token “t41” must be an NT27, but none of the rules that use NT27 on the right-hand side can combine it with the symbols that surround “t41” in the given string.

Running the complete CYK table (or equivalently, enumerating every binary combination allowed by the grammar) therefore leaves the top cell—the span covering the entire 34-token string—empty.  In other words, there is no way to derive the whole string from the start symbol S.

Hence the string is not generated by the grammar.

No
